trump_tweets_words <- trump_tweets_words %>%

In order to get the best prediction, we will filter the tweets to tweets that related to corona, by using key words.

In order to analyze the sentiment of the tweets, we will join the original tweets with the words data. We will count the amount of ‘Positive’ and ‘Negative’ words in each day, and classify each day to be Positive or Negative.

top_with_trump <- only_top_words %>%
  inner_join(trump_tweets_words, by = "word")

# get the amount of each word in certain date
grouped_words <- top_with_trump %>% 
  group_by(Date,sentiment) %>%
  summarise(count_words = n(),.groups='drop')

# each day will include `Positive` and `Negative` columns with the amount of the suitable sentiment words
pivoted_tweets <- pivot_wider(grouped_words, id_cols = NULL, names_from = sentiment, values_from = count_words)
pivoted_tweets[is.na(pivoted_tweets)] <- 0
pivoted_tweets$SentScore<- pivoted_tweets$Positive-pivoted_tweets$Negative
pivoted_tweets$Type<-"Negative"
pivoted_tweets$Type[pivoted_tweets$SentScore>0] <- "Positive"
pivoted_tweets$Type[pivoted_tweets$SentScore==0] <- "Neutral"

Is it possible to predict the level of concern among the american public (Democrats and Republicans) by Donald Trump’s tweets, According to the level of negativity in the tweets, the number of tweets and the number of his tweets’ retweets by day.

Our goal is to find a straight connection between each variable to the concern level. We expect to see that for the Negativity level the concern level will rise as the Negativity level rises especially for the Republicans because they support and believe in Trump’s opinions. For the number of tweets we also expect to find as the amount of tweets in a day rises the concern level also rises. That is because a lot of tweets might indicate emergency and stress. We also expect to see that as the number of retweets on Trump’s tweets rises in a day the concern level also rises, maybe because it’s indicates that the American people (Republicans especially) are involved and concerned about the situation.

tweets_concern <- read_rds(here::here("data", "tweets_concern.rds"))

Build Simple model Simulation

In order to pick the best combination of these three variables, we will build a simple linear regression model and test the different combinations. In the exploration we observed that the relationship between the Democrats and the different variables and the relationship between the Republicans and the different variables is very similar so we decided to build the model based only on the republicans and after we will finish the building process, we will predict on both variables.

simple_model <- function(dataset,engine){
  # set a seed for the model
  set.seed(111)
  # train / test
  train_test_data <- initial_split(rep_tweets_concern)
  covid_train <- training(train_test_data)
  covid_test <- testing(train_test_data)
  # specify model
  covid_mod <- linear_reg(penalty = 0.005, mixture = 1) %>%
    set_engine(engine)
  # build recipe
  covid_rec <- recipe(Republicans ~ ., data = covid_train )
  # build workflow
  covid_wflow <- workflow() %>%
    add_model(covid_mod) %>%
    add_recipe(covid_rec)
  # fit model
  covid_fit <- covid_wflow %>%
    fit(data=covid_train)
  # evaluate model
  covid_train_pred <- predict(covid_fit, covid_train) %>%
    bind_cols(covid_train %>% select(Republicans))
  rmse<-rmse(covid_train_pred, truth = Republicans, estimate = .pred)
  rsq<-rsq(covid_train_pred, truth = Republicans, estimate = .pred)
  return(c(rmse$.estimate[1],rsq$.estimate[1]))
}

Building the linear regression model

First we will select the variables for the model

rep_tweets_concern <- tweets_concern %>%
  select(Republicans,Negative,Sum_rt_per_date,Number_of_tweets)

Now, let’s build the basic model

# Split the data into train and test
set.seed(111)
train_test_data <- initial_split(rep_tweets_concern) 
covid_train <- training(train_test_data)
covid_test  <- testing(train_test_data)

# Specify the model 
covid_mod <- linear_reg(penalty = 0.005, mixture = 1) %>%
  set_engine("glmnet")

# Build recipe
covid_rec <- recipe(Republicans ~ ., data = covid_train)

# Build workflow 
covid_wflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(covid_mod) %>%
  add_recipe(covid_rec)

Next, we will use the k-folds cross validation

set.seed(111)

# Set folds
covid_folds <- vfold_cv(covid_train, v = 11)

# Fit the model  
covid_fit_rs <- covid_wflow %>% 
  fit_resamples(covid_folds,control = control_resamples(save_pred = TRUE))

# Collect the fit results
covid_train_metrics <- collect_metrics(covid_fit_rs)
covid_train_pred <- collect_predictions(covid_fit_rs)

Let’s take a look at the metrics of this model

covid_train_metrics %>% clean_names()

And use the tuning and try to improve the model

# Specify the tuned model 
covid_mod_tune <- linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("glmnet")

# Build the new workflow
covid_wflow_tune <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(covid_mod_tune) %>%
  add_recipe(covid_rec)

# Define the grid
penalty_mixture_grid <- grid_regular(penalty(range = c(-2, 0)),mixture(range=c(0,1)), levels = 5)

# Fit the tuned model  
covid_fit_rs_tune <- tune_grid(
 covid_wflow_tune,
 resamples = covid_folds,
 grid = penalty_mixture_grid,
 control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE)
)

# Collect the fit results
collect_metrics(covid_fit_rs_tune) %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  filter(metric=="rsq") %>%
  arrange(desc(mean)) %>%
  head(5)

We can see that the RSQ is the highest with penalty and mixture values. So let’s build the final model using this parameters.

Building the final model

prediction_model <- function(dataset,col_name){
  
  # Select variables for the model 
  if (col_name=="Democrats"){
    rep_tweets_concern <- dataset %>%
      select(Democrats,Negative,Sum_rt_per_date,Number_of_tweets)
  }
  else{
    rep_tweets_concern <- dataset %>%
      select(Republicans,Negative,Sum_rt_per_date,Number_of_tweets)
  }  
  
  # Split to train and test 
  set.seed(111)
  splits <- initial_split(rep_tweets_concern) 
  covid_train <- training(splits)

  # Build recipe
  if (col_name=="Democrats"){
    covid_rec <- recipe(Democrats ~ ., data = covid_train)
  }
  else{
    covid_rec <- recipe(Republicans ~ ., data = covid_train)
  }

  # Build the new workflow
  covid_wflow_tune <- workflow() %>%
    add_model(covid_mod_tune) %>%
    add_recipe(covid_rec)

  best<-select_best(covid_fit_rs_tune, "rsq")
  
  covid_wflow_final_ds<-finalize_workflow(covid_wflow_tune, best)
  
  # Last fit for the model
  covid_fit_final_ds <- last_fit(
    covid_wflow_final_ds,
    splits)
  
  # Save the model result in a file.
  filename = paste(col_name,".rds",sep="")
  write_rds(covid_fit_final_ds, here::here("model-output", filename), compress = "bz2")
}

Now, we will make the prediction for each group

prediction_model(tweets_concern,"Democrats")
prediction_model(tweets_concern,"Republicans")

Building process summary

In the exploration we observed that there are no strong connections between different variables and the concern level. We will not expect the model to predict the concern level optimally.

As can be seen in the prediction process, at the beginning of the prediction we used simple models of linear regression, and the prediction results were not optimal. After using the simple model, we decided to improve the model by using k-fold cross-validation, the prediction improved. The next improvement was the use of tuning to change the penalty value and the mixture value of the model. Next, we build the final model and forecast in advance on the Democrats’ concern rate and the Republicans’ concern rate.

Conclusions

As we can observe in the graphs and by the high RMSE score and the low R square score the model is not significant. The model does not optimally predict the level of concern of the American public according to the parameters we have defined the sum of retweets and the negativity level of the tweets per day.
